<div class="page-body">
  <span class="section-label">Buyer psychology</span>
  <h2>What the buyer is experiencing</h2>
  <p>By the time a prospective client speaks to you, they are already managing uncertainty. They have done their research. They have formed early impressions. And they are asking themselves questions they may not be able to articulate: can I trust this person? Do they genuinely understand my situation? What happens if this goes wrong?</p>
  <p>These are not logical questions. They are emotional ones. And they are being processed by the part of the brain that handles threat assessment long before rational analysis gets a look in.</p>
  <p>Antonio Damasio's research at the University of Southern California demonstrated this directly. Patients with damage to their emotional processing centres could not make decisions, even when their logical faculties were completely intact. Emotion is not the enemy of good decisions. It is essential to them.</p>
  <p>A sales process built entirely around logic and information misses this reality. The limbic system, which drives all decision-making, needs to feel safe before it can properly assess options. When a buyer feels uncertain or pressured, that safety disappears. So does the decision.</p>

  <span class="section-label">Design principle</span>
  <h2>The outside-in principle</h2>
  <p>The buyer's experience of your sales process is almost certainly different from how you designed it. You see structure, stages, and a logical progression toward a decision. The buyer experiences something else: a series of moments in which they are deciding, consciously or not, whether to trust you enough to go further.</p>
  <p>When you design the process around that reality, starting with how buyers actually think, feel, and make decisions rather than around internal workflows and reporting structures, the friction that kills so many conversations disappears. Buyers feel more autonomous. Decisions come more naturally. The conversations that should convert, do.</p>
</div>

<div class="section-blue">
  <div class="section-blue-inner">
    <span class="section-label">Framework</span>
    <h2>The Trust Triad</h2>
    <p>Through close to thirty years of working with founders and their teams, I have observed that successful sales conversations consistently share three elements. When any one is missing, buyers hesitate. When all three are present, the path to a decision becomes remarkably clear.</p>
    <p>They are not sequential steps. They work together throughout the conversation, each reinforcing the others.</p>

    <p><strong>Qualification.</strong> Rigorous, mutual, and respectful. The goal is clarity for both parties: does genuine alignment exist between what the buyer needs and what you offer? Without that clarity, you risk investing time in conversations that were never going to move forward.</p>

    <p><strong>Credibility.</strong> Credibility in sales is not about credentials or case studies. It comes from demonstrating that you understand the buyer's reality as they are experiencing it. When a buyer senses that you genuinely grasp their situation, not in a general sense but specifically, they feel safe. And when they feel safe, they open up.</p>

    <p><strong>Permission.</strong> Buyers resist when they feel their freedom to choose is being limited. They commit more readily when they feel they have made decisions freely. Permission manifests as small check-ins throughout the conversation that confirm the buyer is comfortable and ready to proceed. The cumulative effect is significant: the buyer feels respected, in control, and part of the process rather than subject to it.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="page-body">
  <span class="section-label">Research</span>
  <h2>The research foundation</h2>
  <p>The frameworks I use are informed by decades of published research across neuroscience, behavioural economics, decision science, and motivation theory. Not as academic exercises, but as practical tools for understanding what is actually happening on the buyer's side of the conversation, and designing processes that work with that reality rather than against it.</p>
</div>

